Gold is widely viewed as a hedge against economic instability. Investors often turn to gold when inflation rises, interest rates change, or when uncertainty in financial markets increases.
Several macroeconomic indicators are commonly believed to influence gold prices. For example, inflation may increase demand for gold as a store of value. Interest rates affect the opportunity cost of holding gold, since gold does not generate interest income. Currency strength also plays a role, because gold is typically priced in U.S. dollars.
This project examines whether these macroeconomic indicators can be used to predict short-term gold price movements using statistical and machine learning techniques.

